Proof of (a).  Let \(n\ge1\) and let \((x_{i})_{i=1}^{n}\) be a decreasing sequence of positive reals:
\[
x_{1}\ge x_{2}\ge\cdots\ge x_{n}>0.
\]
We must show
\[
\Bigl(\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}\Bigr)^{1/2}\;\le\;\sum_{i=1}^{n}\frac{x_{i}}{\sqrt{i}}.
\]
Equivalently, squaring both sides, it suffices to prove
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}
\;\le\;
\Bigl(\sum_{i=1}^{n}\frac{x_{i}}{\sqrt{i}}\Bigr)^{2}
\;=\;
\sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{j=1}^{n}\frac{x_{i}x_{j}}{\sqrt{i\,j}}.
\]
Rearrange the right‐hand side:
\[
\sum_{i,j=1}^{n}\frac{x_{i}x_{j}}{\sqrt{i\,j}}
\;=\;
\sum_{i=1}^{n}\frac{x_{i}^{2}}{i}
\;+\;
\sum_{\substack{1\le i,j\le n\\i\ne j}}
\frac{x_{i}x_{j}}{\sqrt{i\,j}}.
\]
Hence the desired inequality is
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}
\;\le\;
\sum_{i=1}^{n}\frac{x_{i}^{2}}{i}
\;+\;
\sum_{i\ne j}\frac{x_{i}x_{j}}{\sqrt{i\,j}}
\;\Longleftrightarrow\;
\sum_{i\ne j}\frac{x_{i}x_{j}}{\sqrt{i\,j}}
\;\ge\;
\sum_{i=1}^{n}\Bigl(1-\frac1{i}\Bigr)x_{i}^{2}.
\]
Because the left‐hand sum counts each unordered pair \(\{i,j\}\) twice, we write
\[
\sum_{i\ne j}\frac{x_{i}x_{j}}{\sqrt{i\,j}}
\;=\;
2\sum_{1\le i<j\le n}\frac{x_{i}x_{j}}{\sqrt{i\,j}}.
\]
Thus it suffices to show
\[
2\sum_{1\le i<j\le n}\frac{x_{i}x_{j}}{\sqrt{i\,j}}
\;\ge\;
\sum_{i=1}^{n}\Bigl(1-\frac1{i}\Bigr)x_{i}^{2}.
\]
Now for each \(i<j\), since \((x_{k})\) is decreasing we have \(x_{i}\ge x_{j}\), and obviously \(\sqrt{i\,j}\le j\).  Hence
\[
\frac{x_{i}x_{j}}{\sqrt{i\,j}}
\;\ge\;
\frac{x_{j}^{2}}{j}.
\]
Plugging this into the left‐hand side,
\[
2\sum_{1\le i<j\le n}\frac{x_{i}x_{j}}{\sqrt{i\,j}}
\;\ge\;
2\sum_{1\le i<j\le n}\frac{x_{j}^{2}}{j}
\;=\;
2\sum_{j=2}^{n}\frac{j-1}{j}\,x_{j}^{2}
\;=\;
\sum_{j=1}^{n}\frac{2(j-1)}{j}\,x_{j}^{2},
\]
where in the last sum the \(j=1\) term vanishes.  Since for all \(j\ge1\)
\[
\frac{2(j-1)}{j}
\;\ge\;
1-\frac1{j},
\]
we conclude
\[
2\sum_{1\le i<j\le n}\frac{x_{i}x_{j}}{\sqrt{i\,j}}
\;\ge\;
\sum_{j=1}^{n}\Bigl(1-\frac1{j}\Bigr)x_{j}^{2},
\]
as required.  This completes the proof of (a).

\vspace{1ex}
Proof of (b).  Let \((x_{i})_{i=1}^{\infty}\) be a decreasing sequence of positive reals.  We must show there is an absolute constant \(C\) such that
\[
\sum_{m=1}^{\infty}
\frac{1}{\sqrt{m}}\,
\Bigl(\sum_{i=m}^{\infty}x_{i}^{2}\Bigr)^{1/2}
\;\le\;
C\;\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}x_{i}.
\]
Fix \(m\).  The tail \(\{x_{m},x_{m+1},\dots\}\) is again a decreasing positive sequence.  By part (a) applied to the finite initial segment of that tail,
\[
\Bigl(\sum_{i=m}^{\infty}x_{i}^{2}\Bigr)^{1/2}
\;\le\;
\sum_{i=m}^{\infty}\frac{x_{i}}{\sqrt{i-m+1}}.
\]
Hence
\[
\sum_{m=1}^{\infty}
\frac{1}{\sqrt{m}}\,
\Bigl(\sum_{i=m}^{\infty}x_{i}^{2}\Bigr)^{1/2}
\;\le\;
\sum_{m=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{\sqrt{m}}
\;\sum_{i=m}^{\infty}\frac{x_{i}}{\sqrt{i-m+1}}
\;=\;
\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}x_{i}
\;\sum_{m=1}^{i}\frac{1}{\sqrt{m}\,\sqrt{i-m+1}},
\]
where in the last equality we have interchanged the order of summation (all terms are positive).  Define for each fixed \(i\ge1\)
\[
S_{i}
\;=\;
\sum_{m=1}^{i}\frac{1}{\sqrt{m}\,\sqrt{i-m+1}}.
\]
Then
\[
\sum_{m=1}^{\infty}
\frac{1}{\sqrt{m}}\,
\Bigl(\sum_{i=m}^{\infty}x_{i}^{2}\Bigr)^{1/2}
\;\le\;
\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}x_{i}\,S_{i}
\;\le\;
\Bigl(\sup_{i\ge1}S_{i}\Bigr)\;\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}x_{i}.
\]
It remains only to check that \(S_{i}\) is bounded uniformly in \(i\).  Write \(i=2N\) or \(2N+1\).

Case 1:  \(i=2N\).  Then by symmetry
\[
S_{2N}
=\sum_{m=1}^{2N}\frac{1}{\sqrt{m}\,\sqrt{2N-m+1}}
=2\sum_{m=1}^{N}\frac{1}{\sqrt{m}\,\sqrt{2N-m+1}}.
\]
For \(1\le m\le N\) we have \(2N-m+1\ge N+1\), so
\[
\frac{1}{\sqrt{m}\,\sqrt{2N-m+1}}
\;\le\;
\frac{1}{\sqrt{m}\,\sqrt{N+1}}.
\]
Hence
\[
S_{2N}
\;\le\;
\frac{2}{\sqrt{N+1}}
\sum_{m=1}^{N}\frac{1}{\sqrt{m}}
\;\le\;
\frac{2}{\sqrt{N+1}}
\Bigl(1+\int_{1}^{N}\frac{dt}{\sqrt{t}}\Bigr)
\;=\;
\frac{2}{\sqrt{N+1}}\bigl(1+2(\sqrt{N}-1)\bigr)
\,.
\]
The right‐hand expression is easily seen (by checking small \(N\) and the limit as \(N\to\infty\)) to be bounded by \(4\).  Thus
\(\sup_{N}S_{2N}\le4\).

Case 2:  \(i=2N+1\).  A similar symmetry argument gives
\[
S_{2N+1}
=2\sum_{m=1}^{N}\frac{1}{\sqrt{m}\,\sqrt{2N+2-m}}
\;+\;
\frac{1}{N+1}.
\]
Again for \(m\le N\) one has \(2N+2-m\ge N+1\), so the double sum is bounded by
\(\frac{2}{\sqrt{N+1}}\sum_{m=1}^{N}1/\sqrt{m}\le4\)
as before, and the extra term \(1/(N+1)\) is at most \(1\).  Hence
\(\sup_{N}S_{2N+1}\le5\).

Putting the two cases together, we conclude
\[
\sup_{i\ge1}S_{i}\;\le\;5.
\]
Therefore from the chain of inequalities above,
\[
\sum_{m=1}^{\infty}
\frac{1}{\sqrt{m}}\,
\Bigl(\sum_{i=m}^{\infty}x_{i}^{2}\Bigr)^{1/2}
\;\le\;
\Bigl(\sup_{i}S_{i}\Bigr)\;\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}x_{i}
\;\le\;
5\;\sum_{i=1}^{\infty}x_{i}.
\]
Thus one may take \(C=5\), completing the proof of (b).
